Today we joined students and staff at LBJ Early College High School to hear about the amazing programs our Jaguars are engaging in: Fine Arts, Early College High School, AVID, P-Tech, Athletics, CTE and more. Ready for college, career and life!

‚ÄúFrom this program I‚Äôve learned so much about what it means to have hard work ethic,‚Äù
- LBJ senior Zayan, who will be graduating in the spring with an associate degree thru the ECHS program. He plans to major in forensic science or theatre in college.

LBJ student Esmeralda explained the hands-on experience she‚Äôs gained through the Healthcare P-Tech program's partnership with Austin Community College and Seton: "I always knew I wanted to be in the medical field, but I never knew exactly what until I started seeing all of my options in this class."

Mientras nos preparamos para el primer d√≠a de aprendizaje remoto el 8 de septiembre, queremos aprovechar la oportunidad para agradecerle a nuestro personal que ha invertido todo el verano prepar√°ndose para ese d√≠a.

Los miembros del equipo del Distrito Escolar Independiente de Austin han trabajado arduamente para limpiar nuestros planteles entregar comida a las familias, proporcionar tecnolog√≠a, inscribir estudiantes, crear lecciones cautivadoras, ofrecer capacitaci√≥n profesional y mucho m√°s.

As we prepare for the first day of remote learning on September 8th, we wanted to take a moment to thank our staff who have spent all summer getting ready for this day.

Austin ISD team members have worked hard to clean our campuses, deliver food to families, provide technology, register students, create engaging lessons, offer professional training, and so much more.

#AISDProud #WeAreAISD #SomosAISD #AISDAtHome

Austin ISD Food Service
August 5 at 9:09 AM ¬∑

FREE boxes of local produce will be available for families today, Wednesday, August 5, from 9-11 a.m. at Anderson High School, Eastside Memorial Early College High School, LBJ Early College High School, Blanton Elementary and Blackshear Elementary.

This week's Farm Fresh Boxes from The Common Market Texas feature a variety of tasty, locally-grown, organic vegetables.

Big thank you to the Michael & Susan Dell Foundation for supporting this program!

Produce boxes are available at no cost to families with children under the age of 19. Children may accept the boxes, or they will be provided to the adults accompanying children or with documentation of the children they are picking meals up for.

post_text:
P-EBT deadline extended to July 31, 2020

Governor Greg Abbott announced that the Texas Health and Human Services Commission is extending the application deadline for the federal Pandemic-Electronic Benefit Transfer program to July 31. Extending the deadline will help ensure eligible families have time to apply for this one-time food benefit.

P-EBT is a one-time benefit of $285 per eligible child and can be used in the same way as Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program food benefits to pay for groceries. P-EBT is for children who received SNAP in March 2020 and children who attended a school that offered free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 school year. If your child is eligible, apply at yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT.

For more information, please contact 833-613-6220 or visit hhs.texas.gov/PEBT.

Austin ISD is proud to offer streaming of our Community Equity Summit: Our Voices, Our Stories via Facebook Live. If this stream is ever unavailable, please visit AISD.TV or Channel 22 for the official live broadcast of the meeting.

Community Equity Summit: Our Voices, Our Stories

Engage with AISD students, families, teachers, staff, and community members as they share their individual and collective stories about:

- #AISDatHOME: Learning while at home
- How we are investing in equity
- Language Access
- Technology and achieving equitable outcomes

Student art, musical performances & celebrations will be featured!

Hosted by the Austin ISD Office of Equity and Cultural Proficiency & Inclusiveness Office.

There is one week left to apply for P-EBT food benefits. P-EBT is for children who received SNAP March 2020 and children who attended a school that offered free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 school year. If your child is eligible, apply at https://yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT.

For more information, please contact 833-613-6220 or visit hhs.texas.gov/PEBT.

------

Juneteenth Statement from Superintendent Paul Cruz and Board of Trustees:

Juneteenth celebrates June 19, 1865, when enslaved people in Texas received word about the official end of the Civil War‚Äîtwo and a half years after the Emancipation Proclamation was signed.

It has been 155 years since freedom was announced in Texas, yet today‚Äôs continued marginalization, mistreatment and killing of Black people has ignited protests in all 50 states and worldwide.

We respect everyone‚Äôs first amendment right to free speech and stand with protestors to proclaim: Enough is enough. Black Lives Matter.

Juneteenth is a time to reflect on the past and resolve for a better future. To quote Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., ‚ÄúInjustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.‚Äù

https://www.austinisd.org/announcements/2020/06/09/juneteenth-statement-from-superintendent-paul-cruz-and-board-trustees

#AISDProud #WeAreAISD #SomosAISD #AllAreWelcome

post_text:
The top-ranking high school students from all over Austin ISD gathered virtually on Thursday June 11 to celebrate their achievements with Superintendent Paul Cruz. Personalized large pizzas were delivered to every top student by Austin's Pizza with a note saying, "We wish we could have met in person to honor your achievement. Instead, we will socialize in the virtual world. Please enjoy this pizza as we celebrate YOU and your next SLICE of life!"

Students shared stories of their favorite teachers, biggest achievements, college/career plans, and insightful feedback on the future of AISD. Additional guests included Sheila Henry, Executive Director of High School Operations and Reyne Telles, Executive Director of Communications. The class of 2020 top students were also able to watch the premier of this year's Top Ranking Student Testimonial Video. The celebration ended with a Happy Birthday song to two top students who share a June 11 birthday, Olivia from Travis and Blair from McCallum.

#AISDProud of our #AISDGrads!

#WeAreAISD #SomosAISD #AISDGameChangers

shared_text:
Austin ISD Food Service
June 1 at 9:34 AM ¬∑

We are #AISDProud to provide meals to caregivers at all Austin ISD meal sites, while also supporting the local economy. Over the past two weeks we have served around 60,000 meals, prepared by local restaurants, to caregivers who are accompanying their children to meal sites, or picking meals up for their children. Big thanks to Easy Tiger, Henbit, Emmer & Rye, and Good Work Austin, a collective of Austin restaurants (L'Oca D'Oro, Colleen's Kitchen, Contigo Austin), for providing these amazing meals for our families.

Caregiver meals are made possible through funding from the City of Austin and the AISD Crisis Support Fund, established by the Austin Ed Fund.

Find all meal services sites, times and more info: austinisd.org/covid19/meals.

üì∑: Easy Tiger

Salute is AISD‚Äôs annual celebration to recognize some of the district‚Äôs outstanding team members for their continued dedication to student excellence and achievement in our schools.

This year, to ensure the district maintains a safe environment during COVID-19, the Office of Human Capital and Talent Acquisition and Development team, Austin Partners in Education and Channel 22 are instead hosting a virtual Salute 2020 Celebration to honor the great work of our staff and recognize all of our award finalists and winners.

As the main event, our special virtual Salute Awards Ceremony will be broadcast on AISD.TV on Wednesday, May 20 at 6:30pm! Friends, families, and the community are invited to tune in, host virtual watch parties, and celebrate their nominees and award winners on social media using the #AISDSalute2020.

Thank you Capital Metro for partnering with Austin ISD to provide Wi-Fi hotspots to students living in neighborhoods with the greatest need. The goal of this program is to give students internet access to work on assignments and finish homework.

AISD has been providing Wi-Fi hotspots on our school buses since early April. Every weekday, 110 district buses provide internet access to students at multiple locations from 8:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m. Capital Metro will now send MetroAccess vehicles to locations from 2:00 p.m. to 8:00 p.m. to supplement the AISD service times.

Locations and more info:
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1psGWsoqdjDySEr8lIVrkJ9Vfo2-Imk0G/view

Austin ISD Food Service
April 27 at 7:42 AM ¬∑

Starting today (4/27), Anderson High School and Oak Hill Elementary will be added to the list of Austin ISD curbside meal sites.

Meals will be available for any child under 19, Monday-Friday from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m.. On Friday, families may receive six meals per child under the age of 19 (a breakfast and a lunch for Friday, Saturday, and Sunday). We recommend families bring bags to help get their weekend meals home safely on Fridays.

These curbside meal sites were approved by the Texas Department of Agriculture following a recent update.

Find meal sites, times and more info: austinisd.org/covid19/meals

post_text:
It has been several weeks since our campuses closed, and the shift to Continuous Learning has been anything but business as usual. What is not unusual is the fact that our students depend on us to bring normalcy, balance and often basic needs to their lives. While we cannot offer the comfort of warm hugs or a classroom of peers, we can still do our best to guide our students through their complex emotions.

Thank you for all you are doing, Austin ISD! Watch this video that highlights your good work.

#AISDProud #AISDAtHome #AISDGameChangers

Board Information Session begins at 6:00 p.m. Watch the full broadcast beginning at 6:00 p.m. on AISD.TV, Facebook Live and Cable Channel 22 in Austin.
**********************************
Please note, these comments are not monitored. So that we can be sure your question gets to the right person and is answered as quickly as possible, please visit the district's Learning at Home/COVID-19 Let's Talk page: https://www.austinisd.org/letstalk.
Many answers are also available on the Frequently Asked Questions section of the district's COVID-19 webpage: https://www.austinisd.org/covid19/faq.
This situation is continuously changing. Every day brings new information and new considerations for how to best approach educating our students. We know the uncertainty is difficult and we are working hard to share information as we are able to. Thank you for your patience and support as we work together to offer online instruction and feed our students while doing our best to keep our amazing staff, students and families safe and healthy.

post_text:
When the COVID-19 pandemic struck Austin, Garza Independence High School Principal Dr. Linda Webb decided to act.

‚ÄúI was watching the news one night, and they were talking about the need for masks. I knew that AISD workers were going out and feeding our kids, and I was worried,‚Äù Webb said. ‚ÄúI picked up the phone and called my quilting group, and I told them what was happening. We all immediately got to work.‚Äù

The group went from making 40 masks to several hundred in weeks. Masks began to be distributed all over the community, including a veterans hospital, a retirement home as well as to first responders and medical staff.

#AISDProud of Dr. Webb and everyone supporting our community!

Read the story here:
https://www.austinisd.org/announcements/2020/04/16/austin-isd-principal-sews-masks-community-need

#AISDGameChangers #InThisTogether #AISDAtHome Austin ISD Food Services

#AISDProud of Anderson High School engineering teacher, Joe Ngo, for 3D printing and manufacturing face shields to support our local hospitals and healthcare workers!

From Anderson High School, Austin Texas:
We just wanted to take a moment to brag about Anderson engineering teacher Joe Ngo. When the schools closed down, he collaborated with ATX Hackerspace and people with 3D printers in the area to manufacture face shields for hospitals that have been hit hard by the pandemic. Last week, they created and sent out 150 task masks, and expect to send 300 this week.

Even when the world is going through these unique and tumultuous times, there are always opportunities to find ways to help.

#AISDGameChangers

International High School shared a video of Student Council members and staff giving messages of support for the community and tips to stay healthy! ‚ù§Ô∏è

#AISDProud #AISDGameChangers #AISDAtHome #SomosAISD

-----

International High School welcomes the world‚Äôs students to Austin. New Texans from Africa, Asia, Europe, the Middle East and the Americas begin their studies in a global community where every student is bilingual or multilingual.

International High School prepares students to transition to public education in the United States and sets them on a course for success. The school offers tutoring and other programs to help students adapt to their new lives in America, while building the skills they need to succeed in college, career and life.

Educators that are well-experienced in teaching students who speak English as a second language work with students to develop individual academic plans with an emphasis on higher education.

Educators that are well-experienced in teaching students who speak English as a second language work with students to develop individual academic plans with an emphasis on higher education.

post_text:
Our meal distribution program during campus closures has seen a tremendous response, with tens of thousands of meals served daily. We're thrilled that the community is using the program, and we need to focus our resources on serving students (age 19 and younger).
Starting Monday, April 6th, we will no longer be distributing meals for parents or caregivers. Individuals age 19 and older are encouraged to reach out to the Central Texas Food Bank for food assistance at this time.
Meals may still be provided to parents or caregivers for children, even when the child is not present, provided they have one of the following forms of documentation at the point of meal service.

- Official letter/email from school that shows children as enrolled
- Individual student report cards
- Attendance record from Parent Portal of school website
- Birth certificate for children not in school
- Student ID cards

shared_text:
Austin ISD Food Service
March 30 at 5:16 AM ¬∑

Update 3/30:
Following the recent update by the Texas Department of Agriculture, schools are now authorized to provide meals to parents for their child ‚Äì even when the child is not present - provided they have one of the following forms of documentation at the point of meal service:
‚Ä¢ Official Letter/email from school that shows children as enrolled
‚Ä¢ Individual student report cards
‚Ä¢ Attendance record from parent portal of school website
‚Ä¢ Birth certificate for children not in school
‚Ä¢ Student Id cards

Safety instructions for Austin ISD meal sites:
- At curbside sites parents will tape the documentation to their car window or dash so staff may review through the glass.
- At bus stops sites, parents will place the documentation on the table for staff to review.

If the parent does not have documentation, the child(ren) must be present to receive a meal.

post_text:
The Austin ISD Social and Emotional Learning team is celebrating #SELday today! Reminding one another that we are #InThisTogether!

Take care of yourselves and each other, friends!

Austin Mayor Steve Adler has officially made today Austin SEL Day! Although we're spatially distant to prevent spreading COVID-19, we can still spread #love! #SELebrate with us today by posting on social media, participating in online contests, & sharing videos & activities:
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NQGqWQjpf37VrMxIpZXzWNSd-6peZIyP6XungPVhroY/edit?usp=sharing

Social and Emotional Learning (SEL) is a process for helping children and adults develop fundamental skills for life effectiveness. SEL teaches the skills we all need to handle ourselves, our relationships, and our work effectively and ethically. These skills include:

- recognizing and managing our emotions,
- developing caring and concern for others,
- establishing positive relationships,
- making responsible decisions, and
- handling challenging situations constructively and ethically.

#AISDProud #AISDGameChangers #AISDAtHome

üó≥Did you know each year right before the graduation ceremonies, Austin ISD partners with the Travis County Tax Office to register #AISDGrads to vote? üéì

We registered a total of 591 Class of 2019 #AISDGrads from 14 campuses at graduation last May at the Frank Erwin Center!

Graduates were able to use the wait time before walking the stage to register to vote. In a partnership with Travis County's Tax Office, students learned about the importance of registering to vote and voting, as well as how to seek out nonpartisan information on candidates and issues.

Don't forget to go vote today in the Joint Primary Elections!

Polls are open today, March 3rd from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. for the Joint Primary Elections. Travis County polling locations and other Election Day information can be found here: votetravis.com

"Issues we have around race and racism, we must start to face them."
Courageous conversations are happening. David Crockett High School, McCallum High School - Austin, TX and O. Henry Middle School #AISDProud Students Organized for Anti-Racism are sitting in a racial equity leadership seminar by Pacific Educational Group.

The principals of the schools have previously participated in the same seminar to better assist their campus in engaging in race conversations. It includes learning to stay engaged, how to handle experiencing discomfort, speak their truth and expect/accept non-closure.

#AISDSOAR #AISDEquity

post_text:
Thank you for joining us at the UT/AISD Collaborative Research Forum at the AISD Performing Arts Center!

The purpose of the forum is to foster greater awareness of the work that university and school district researchers are conducting in pre-kindergarten through 12th grade settings (PK-12), share key findings, identify unanswered questions, and establish new collaborations.

The event is coordinated by the UT/AISD Research Collaborative, and is supported by the Office of the Dean of the The College of Education at The University of Texas at Austin and AISD Department of Research and Evaluation (https://www.austinisd.org/dre).

The UT/AISD Research Collaborative is an ongoing, communicative body made up of members from the College of Education and leadership within AISD. We come together to work on areas of shared interest including teacher development, leadership pathways, and fostering shared research opportunities.

#AISDProud #AISDGameChangers #SomosAISD #AllAreWelcome

Austin ISD Food Service
January 29 at 11:53 AM ¬∑

Dispersed dining is one of the many ways we are expanding healthy food access at Austin ISD. This week we launched our second mini-market pilot. The Square Fare Fridge at Navarro Early College High School offers healthy, tasty grab-n-go items during breakfast and lunch, in a location convenient to students outside the cafe. Our dispersed dining pilot programs at Navarro ECHS and James Bowie High School Austin, Texas are made possible through support from the Michael & Susan Dell Foundation.

Check out these highlights from last week in our district:

- Metz and Sanchez hosted their eighth annual No Place for Hate MLK Peace Walk.
- Bowie High School teacher Bowman Brannon received a SUPERintendent Coin.
- The district partnered with the Thinkery to celebrate refugee and immigrant families in Austin ISD schools and communities.
- The Northeast Raiders band along with students, staff and families marched in the 27th annual MLK March.
- CapMetro unveiled its first two electric buses which feature Campbell Elementary student artwork.
- Students tackled the difficult topics of racism, hatred, inequality and social injustice as they relate to modern society at the 15th annual MLK Oratory Competition.
And more! Watch this week's AISD in 3.

Austin ISD will be closed for the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday, Monday, Jan. 20.

All AISD offices and schools will be closed during this period. The district will resume regular business and school hours Tuesday, Jan. 21.

We encourage everyone to use the hashtag #AISDMLK to show us how your school is celebrating the life and legacy of Martin Luther King Jr. with your students and community:
https://austinisd.org/announcements/2020/01/16/aisd-will-participate-austin-area-heritage-council-annual-mlk-march

For information about upcoming AISD holidays and events, please visit the district's calendar at www.austinisd.org/calendar.

post_text:
Thank you for joining us for the modernized Menchaca Elementary Grand Opening Celebration! Menchaca Elementary has been designed through an extensive process that engaged teachers, parents and students.

The buildings form two courtyards linked by a second-story bridge that houses an innovative library media center and maker spaces specifically designed for the school. More than 30 percent of the site is open, vegetated space, creating direct links between the outdoors and learning environments.

Thank you to our #AISDGameChangers and to all who helped make this #AISDModernized, state-of-the-art facility a reality for our students: AISD community, AISD Board of Trustees, teachers and team members, Facility and Bond Planning Advisory Committee, Menchaca Campus Architectural Team (CAT), AECOM, LPA Inc. and
Joeris General Contractors, Ltd.

We‚Äôre #AISDProud to build our #AISDFuture!

Learn more:
https://www.austinisd.org/announcements/2020/01/13/modernized-menchaca-elementary-opens-its-doors

#AISDFuture #AISDFuturo #AllAreWelcome #SomosAISD
Menchaca PTA Menchaca Elementary Library

shared_text:
Austin Watershed
January 13 at 1:25 PM ¬∑

You probably already know that cisterns capture & hold rainwater, which you can use to water landscapes in drier times. But did you also know that cisterns are a valuable tool for combatting property drainage & erosion problems caused by Central Texas storms? We recently installed 12 large rainwater cisterns at Reilly Elementary School as part of our Rain Catcher Pilot Program! www.austintexas.gov/raincatcherpilot #aisdgreen Austin Parks and Recreation Department

Three Austin ISD students had the opportunity to turn on the lights at the 2019 Austin Trail of Lights Opening Ceremonies to welcome all the guests! The students were winners in a districtwide essay contest where they wrote about their identity and what makes them unique üìù This year was our best year yet, with over 160 entries.

Congratulations to first place winner Arely R. of Perez Elementary, and runners up Katie M. of Bryker Woods Elementary and Hennesys M. of Govalle Elementary! We are #AISDProud of you!

Read their award winning essays in this post!

Cultivating Tomorrow‚Äôs Teachers is a program for students in Ready, Set, Teach at Akins and Navarro early college high schools. Austin ISD will partner with universities to grow and increase the number of culturally proficient teachers, accelerate teacher certification and bring former AISD students into our classrooms. Graduates will teach at Paredes and Burnet middle schools, where students will benefit from learning from teachers who share their race, ethnicity and life experiences.

Frozen schools were announced this afternoon for the 2020‚Äì21 school year. These are campuses that have or are expected to have enrollment that is greater than their capacity. List is below, and lots more info is at www.austinisd.org/transfer.

High schools: Akins ECHS and Navarro ECHS, Austin, Bowie and McCallum

Middle schools: Gorzycki, Lively, Lamar and Murchison

Elementary schools: Baldwin, Baranoff, Becker (except dual language), Blazier, Brentwood, Casis, Cowan, Doss, Gullett (except kindergarten), Hill, Kiker, Lee (except kindergarten), Maplewood, Mathews (except kindergarten), Menchaca, Mills, Oak Hill, Reilly (except dual language through fourth grade), Ridgetop (except dual language), Summitt (except dual language), Sunset Valley (except dual language through fourth grade) and Zilker (except kindergarten).

We understand the high cost of child care and we want to be part of the solution. post_text:
Travis Early College High School culinary students were joined with parents, staff, Dr. Cruz, Trustee Ashy and other community members in the campus' Tamalada, which aims to share the Latino culture of making tamales each holiday season.

Everyone came together to prepare and assemble a variety of tamales to share with the community!

Tamaladas, or tamale-making parties, have been a tradition in many Latino families for generations. Multiple families and generations gather during the holiday season to cook, assemble, and eat the dish. In a Tamalada, everyone from children to grandparents, have specific jobs. From cooking fillings to kneading masa and preparing wrappers, all members of the community play a part.

#AISDProud #AISDGameChangers #SomosAISD #AllAreWelcome

Air Force Junior ROTC students at Bowie High School toured a Texas Army National Guard UH-60 Blackhawk helicopter and talked with aircrew and other aviation professionals today.

Students also learned about the STEM aspects of careers in aviation and emergency rescue.

William Black, a former James Bowie High School student and current Chief Warrant Officer 3 in the Texas Army National Guard, co-piloted the mission to the campus.

Special thanks to Texas Army National Guard Colonel Macgregor, Pilot Chief Warrant Officer Black, and Austin Fire Department Captain Bartell for being here to teach our students about the science of aviation and logistics of natural disaster emergency rescue!

#AISDProud #AISDGameChangers #AllAreWelcome #SomosAISD Texas Military Department

Rosedale School enjoyed their annual Thanksgiving Luncheon with students, families and staff!

Rosedale School is a place for families whose children have severe special needs. The school offers one simple message: Your child is welcome here.

Rosedale's well-experienced educators serve students who have significant disabilities, including children who are medically fragile or who need intensive behavioral support.

Austin ISD and the Rosedale School are looking forward to master planning for their modernization as part of the 2017 Bond. Hear from the Rosedale School community by watching this video:
https://vimeo.com/88716962

Learn more about the Rosedale School modernization here:
https://austinisd2017bond.org/schools/rosedale/

More information on Rosedale School: https://rosedaleproud.org/

November 22, 2019 at 4:12 PM ¬∑

Rosedale School enjoyed their annual Thanksgiving Luncheon with students, families and staff!

Rosedale School is a place for families whose children have severe special needs. The school offers one simple message: Your child is welcome here.

Rosedale's well-experienced educators serve students who have significant disabilities, including children who are medically fragile or who need intensive behavioral support.

Austin ISD and the Rosedale School are looking forward to master planning for their modernization as part of the 2017 Bond. Hear from the Rosedale School community by watching this video:
https://vimeo.com/88716962

Learn more about the Rosedale School modernization here:
https://austinisd2017bond.org/schools/rosedale/

More information on Rosedale School: https://rosedaleproud.org/

post_text: We are #AISDProud to say that Austin ISD‚Äôs revised Human Sexuality & Responsibility lessons and handouts for grades 3 through 8 are now available in their entirety on the district‚Äôs website: https://www.austinisd.org/pe-health/health-education/hsr. Trustees unanimously approved the new lessons Oct. 28, and teachers will begin using the lessons in May. The lessons and resources‚Äîupdated for the first time in 11 years‚Äîprovide students with medically accurate, age-appropriate information. Topics include safe use of social media, differences in family structures, bullying, how to identify a trusted adult, and much more. Lessons are also available in school libraries. Families may opt their children out of one, several or all lessons. For more information, please visit the HSR webpage or contact your student‚Äôs campus.

Happy #WorldKindnessDay! The purpose of World Kindness Day is to highlight good deeds in the community focusing on the positive power and the common thread of kindness which binds us.

Ali, a sophomore at Ann Richards School for Young Women Leaders, was the imagination and drive behind this service project at Boone Elementary. Ali and fellow ARS students Lucy, Melanie and SaNaya, worked on giving the bathrooms a makeover by painting kind, positive messages for Boone Bears students!

Feel free to share how you've seen kindness spread in our #AISDProud schools!

Austin ISD once again took part in Jumpstart‚Äôs Read for the Record this year, a national campaign launched more than a decade ago to highlight the importance of building early literacy and language skills for all children.

On Read for the Record day today‚Äînow in its 14th year‚Äîpeople nationwide read the same book to children as part of the world‚Äôs largest shared reading experience.

This year's featured book, "Thank You, Omu!" tells the story of a generous elderly woman who makes a fantastic pot of stew, which brings together her community.

Dr. Cruz was one of the guest readers at Pleasant Hill Elementary Austin! After listening to the story, second-graders practiced adding ingredients to make their own community stew! üç≤üçÖü•¶ü•ï

Austin ISD is proud to partner with H-E-B and the Austin Trail of Lights to host the Holiday Writing Contest. Students in grades 3-5 are eligible to write an essay up to 250 words in response to the prompt:

There is no one quite like you! Your identity is made up of all the characteristics that make you special, unique, and wonderful. Some parts of your identity can be seen on the outside and others cannot. What aspects of your identity are most important to you and why? What makes you YOU?

Teachers and parents/guardians may submit their child or students' work. All essays must be submitted through this website or this link. Submissions must be done by this Friday, November 8.

More info:
https://sites.google.com/austinisd.org/aisdtrailoflights/home

#AISDProud #AISDGameChangers #AllAreWelcome Aisd Humanities

TRIO Electric Pre-Apprenticeship Program Commitment Ceremony
@ Navarro Early College High School
October 29, 2019

Through this program, students will learn how to become productive and safe electricians, earn industry certifications, a level-one certificate from ACC and if eligible, have the opportunity to earn money through internships and eventually a full time job.

#AISDProud of our students entering this program!

Austin ISD Fine Arts proudly presents the 2019 Choral Festival on Tuesday, October 29 at 7 p.m held in the AISD Performing Arts Center, 1500 Barbara Jordan Blvd. The concert features students from the AISD Elementary Honor Choir and 6th Grade Honor Choir.

For more information contact Patricia Moreno at patricia.h.moreno@austinisd.org or 512-414-4191.
